§6Wetware Lifesupport Circuit Boards§r are the basis of §6Wetware§r circuits, the final theme that spans tiers six through nine.

Heavy.

Avoid dropping it on your foot.

Using plain §3Steam Dynamos§f is pretty inefficient.

It's strongly recommended to make §aaugments§r. With these, you can turn one Steam Dynamo into a §3steam boiler§f, and two other Steam Dynamos into §3steam turbines§f. The ratio is always §a1:2§r if all Dynamos are equally upgraded.

This greatly increases the overall efficiency and the amount of power produced, from §a40 RF/t§r per basic steam dynamo to §a320 RF/t§r per set of three augmented dynamos.

This quest, and the ones that follow it, are §cNOT REQUIRED§r for progression.

Only do them if you want to be able to explore the various planets offered by Advanced Rocketry and potentially build bases there, or in space.

Refer to the various high quality tutorials on AR available on youtube for specifics.

§aWarp Core§r is a multiblock structure that you can build on the space station. Use the Holo-Projector for a building guide.

While it's not required for the progression, you can spend some resources to travel to distant planets, either to explore them or just to change the background of your space station.

The Input Hatch must be filled with Dilithium.
Dilithium Crystals are used to power Warp Cores, and are also a key component in several Micro Miner missions.

The Fourth Micro Miner.

Brings you first bits of §6Osmium and Iridium§r when provided with Wither Realm Data.

When equipped with Composition Sensor, brings §6Oilsands Ore§r.

When equipped with Gemstone Sensor, brings:
§6* Dense Redstone Ore
* Dense Emerald Ore
* Dense Diamond Ore
* Dense Lapis Ore
* Dense Coal Ore§r

The Fifth Micro Miner.

The only source of §6Naquadah Dust§r.

When provided with §6Stabilized Uranium§r, brings:
§6* Uranium 238 Ore
* Molybdenite Ore
* Tennantite Ore
* Bastnasite Ore
* Sphalerite Ore
* Palladium Ore
* Beryllium Ore
* Monazite Ore
* Osmium Ore
* Enderpearl §mOre§r§6 Blocks
* Boron Dust§r

The Sixth Micro Miner.

The first decent source of §6Dragon Eggs§r and §6Einsteinium§r.

Is also useful for:
§6* Uranium 238 Ore
* Iridium Ore
* Osmium Ore

The Seventh Micro Miner.

The source of §6Dragon Hearts§r and the valuable §6Lair of The Chaos Guardian Data§r.

As a bonus, brings §6Dragon Eggs, Dragon's Breath, Ender Dragon Scales§r and a plenty of different precious metals and gems.

Your first MV hull is as good of a place as any to consider yourself graduated from LV.

You might notice that these hulls can be made more cheaply in an §3Assembling Machine§r, but you don't have that weird fluid. Don't worry, you'll be able to make that soon.

§3Electrolyzers§r use electricity to separate items into their more basic components.

For example, you can break down Water into §9Hydrogen Gas§r and §9Oxygen Gas§r, or break down §6Clay Dust§r into §6Sodium Dust§r, §6Silicon Dust§r, §6Lithium Dust§r, and §6Aluminium Dust§r.

Provides more augment slots to machines and dynamos.

Dynamos operate at §a500% of base power and fuel burn rate§r.

Portable Tanks hold §a800 buckets§r.

Machines operate at §a400% of base speed§r.
Purified Galena, Purified Sphalerite and Sulfuric Acid can be used to make Tiny Piles of Indium.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth And Final Tier Four Circuits
betterquesting:10.desc:8: With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §aQuantum Circuit§r.
Arsenic can be obtained through the electrolysis of Cobaltite.
Radon will be needed in large quantities, and for now, you'll need to obtain it from Tier Two Micro Miner missions.
With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Take these parts and combine them with three §aQuantum Circuits§r to craft a §aQuantum Processor§r.

Macerators are useful for grinding things down. The best application for one right now would be grinding down clay or terracotta into §6Clay Dust§f.

LV Macerators lack byproduct slots. MV Macerators get one byproduct slot, but unfortunately the §6Stone Dust§r byproduct is prioritized so in practice you get a bit less than advertised. HV Macerators and better have all three slots.

Macerator byproduct chances are doubled for each tier after MV. Here's the list of chances for ore byproducts for a quick reference:
§a§r• LV: §c0%
§r• MV: §a14%§c*
§r• HV: §a28%
§r• EV: §a56%
§r• IV and better: §a100%§r

The first tier of §6capacitors§r. These (or stronger versions) are required to make §bEnderIO§r machines run. They're also used as components in a variety of recipes.

Higher tier capacitors will significantly increase the speed at which these machines operate, among other machine-specific properties.

Mixes two dusts to make a third.

For now, you'll be using it to make Glowstone Dust and Energetic Blend.

Glowstone Dust is made from Phosphor Dust and Gold Dust, or you could gather it from the Nether.

Energetic Blend is made from Glowstone Dust and Redstone Dust.
§6Luminessence§r is used in a number of things, but right now, it will be a component in your §aExtended Crafting Tables§r.
§9Phosphorus§r, §9Oxygen§r, and §9Water§r combine together into §9Phosphoric Acid§r.

Carry morest stuff.

What more explanation are you expecting?
You can combine various items with a §6Blank Data Model§r for a completed §6Data Model§r that you can run inside the §3Simulation Chamber§r.
Man, that's a LOT of quests linked to this one.

Before you travel to the Moon, you'll want to set up a way to easily return.

Lay out nine of the §6Telepad Blocks§r in a 3x3 pattern. They should turn into a multiblock. While having some §6Paper§r in your inventory, use the §aCoordinate Selector§r to create a §6Location Printout§r of an area near the Telepad. Keep track of this Printout and make sure to bring it with you to the Moon!

Make sure the Telepad on the Overworld is ready to go. It needs power, a tank of §9Dew of the Void§r, and the chunk it's in needs to be §eChunkloaded§r. Bring the other nine Telepad Blocks with you when you go to the Moon, and once there, set up a similar layout. The one on the Moon will also need power, Dew of the Void and its chunk loaded. Consider making a solar panel and a capacitor bank to keep it powered.

Once your Moon Telepad is up and running, put your Overworld coordinates into it. Then record your current location on the Moon with the Coordinate Selector. Teleport home, and put those coordinates into the Overworld Telepad. Now you can travel back and forth easily!

You might consider building a room dedicated to Telepad transit, both on the Overworld and to other Planets, and label them. You'll be visiting many other worlds soon enough.

Fluix is initially made via in-world crafting, by dropping §6Redstone Dust§r, §6Nether Quartz§r, and a §6Charged Certus Quartz Crystal§r in the same block of §9Water§r. You'll see some sparks then the items will merge into a §6Fluix Crystal§r. Be sure to turn off any nearby item magnets/collectors or they might interrupt this crafting process.

The §3Energy Acceptor§r converts RF power into AE power that Applied Energistics uses, in a 2 RF to 1 AE ratio. This power will be transmitted through adjacent full-block ME Network devices, as well as along all connected §6ME Cables§r, §6ME Conduits§r, and §6Quartz Fiber§r. 

Quartz Fiber are §emicroparts§r you can put between an ME Cable and any ME Network block or another ME Cable. This will allow transmission of AE power but not data, which is useful for having data-isolated ME Networks all sharing the same power source.

The next step in the circuit grind.

You'll also need access to HSS-G ingots to make this machine.

This pack has §bBuilding Gadgets§r.

These good stuffs can help you building, destroy massive areas or even copy-paste blocks. The latter won't make blocks out of thin air though, so you have to have them in your inventory.

By default, the config GUI is bound to §6G§r.

Not a project for the faint of heart.

Make sure your power and circuit production are up to the challenge before you try to build this.

Notice that all numbers of required items are multiples of 12. This is to make an Assembly Line that's 12 units long, allowing for 12 inputs. 12 is enough to make a Fusion Reactor Controller Mk1, but you'll need an even longer Line for later projects.

The Fluid Input Hatches can replace any of the Steel Casings along the bottom outside except for the Casings touching the Output Bus. The Energy Input Hatches along the top can be replaced by Steel Casings, and you only need the one Energy Input Hatch (although you can add more if you want). The Input Buses along the bottom must be ULV tier, nothing else.

Time to get fusing!

The Fusion Reactor is a multiblock that fuses fluids. Some people call it an overpriced Tinker's smeltery. This one is less flexible than the previous GregTech multiblocks, as you can only put hatches where the preview shows.

The preview shows §aall valid spots§r, but you don't actually need that many fluid hatches. You can replace any of the hatch positions in the structure with §aLuV Machine Casings§r, as long as you have at least §atwo Fluid Input Hatches§r and §aone Fluid Output Hatch§r. It's possible to use input/output hatches in every valid location, if you prefer.

Because of this, the quest only asks for §a80 LuV Machine Casings§r. If you want to use the minimum number of fluid hatches, you'll need to craft an additional §a28 casings§r.

Each §aEnergy Input Hatch§r increases the reactor's power buffer. The "Energy to Start" value of a recipe is drained instantly when the reactor switches from the previous recipe it ran to a different one. §aAll 16 Energy Input Hatches§r are required to be able to process all Mark 1 recipes.

Fusion Reactors don't overclock, so you will eventually want to make more.

You'll need at least §6Naquadah Coil Blocks§r in your blast furnace to smelt §6Draconium§r, as well as a healthy supply of §9Cetane Diesel§r to reach the immense heat it takes to liquefy.

Draconium gets so hot that it requires the potent coolant §9Gelid Cryotheum§r to aid your §3Vacuum Freezer§r in turning it into usable ingots.
Another good use for Helium.

...or, well, you might just do some exploration and kill a wild thermal elemental for a rod.

Spend it well to craft a thermal elemental model. The rest of dusts can be crafted from pristine matter.

Saves you from getting knee-deep into chemistry for a bucket of Elemental Reduction Fluid if you're not playing on Peaceful.
You'll need an IV Precision Laser Engraver for this craft.
The culmination of so much effort.

Obtaining §6Grains of Infinity§r will require you to mine all the way down to Bedrock level.

Use Flint and Steel to light a fire (or many fires) and then wait for it to go out. There's a 50% chance of Grains Of Infinity to appear for every fire that burns out on its own.

But who wants to do that forever? There will be better ways before too long, don't worry.

There are at least three different ways to produce Epoxy, with the common factor being Epichlorohydrin.

Bisphenol A can be produced from either petrochem products, or via pyrolyzing wood to distill Charcoal Byproducts into useful components. Alternatively, you can pyrolyze coal for just Phenol.
You might also be interested in distilling Fermented Biomass as it provides a considerable amount of products.

Or you can just straight mix Naphtha with Nitrogen Dioxide and Epichlorohydrin. This is easier overall but yields less epoxy in comparison, however if you're producing a lot of oil then it's a viable choice.

The final decision is down to you make. Check out recipes in JEI.

You'll need large quantities of §6Canola§f (for §6Canola Oil§f in a §bCanola Press§f) and §6Sugarcane§f (for §6Ethanol§f).

Of course, other crops can work as well, if you want to mix things up.

betterquesting:10.desc:8: Creating Draconium is a complex process, but you'll want to automate every step of it, since you'll be needing quite a lot of Draconium in the long run.
HV Batteries function the same as LV and MV, only requiring more resources to craft.

You may have noticed that The End portals in Strongholds are disabled.

The only way to access The End is to... §ebake a cake§r. You can refill it with §6Eyes of Ender§r.

Prepare some gear, eat a slice, and get ready for a fight!

Find a clever way to make the Ender Dragon's Egg to fall onto a torch. This neat trick will turn it into a collectible item so you can bring it home with you.

You might be interested in getting yourself a §3Dragon Egg Mill§r to place it on for free 500 GP.

§9Fire Water§r is a great way of producing §6Grains of Infinity§r. Spill a bucket over a patch of bare bedrock and watch it drop grains every so often. There's a 2% chance per tick for one to be generated on each block of bedrock the Fire Water is flowing on.

Make sure to chunkload the area.

The full complexity of Nuclearcraft is far too much for the scope of this quest guide, so you're encouraged to watch a tutorial or read a guide online. For the purposes of this particular quest, you'll be building a cheap breeder reactor to works towards Plutonium.

First, set up your 56 Reactor Casings to encase a 3x3 cube shape of empty air. The Casings should only cover the faces of the interoir cube, not the edges or corners. You should have exactly the right number of Casings to encase a 3x3 space.

Now open a hole so you can look into the cube and set up the interior. The Reactor Cells will go in all 8 corners. Then the Lapis Coolers will go inbetween them, 4 on top layer and 4 on the bottom layer. At this point, the top and botom layers should have eight blocks each with an empty middle, and the middle layer fully empty. Then in the middle layer, place the 4 Graphite blocks on the corners, and the 4 Glowstone Coolers on the sides (so they touch both Lapis Coolers). Now the cube should be full, except for an empty column in the middle. The reactor will now be complete when you reseal it up with the Casings you removed to access the interior.

Finally, place the Fission Reactor Controller along any edge or corner of the reactor. Opening the Reactor Controller should let you know that the structure was properly formed, if not, go back and check what you did wrong.
You don't need it just yet, but you can make it now.

If you don't want to mine Obsidian by hand, consider using a Fluid Solidifier to turn §cLava§r into §6Obsidian Blocks§r for you. The process is slow and energy intensive, though.

§3Fluid Solidifiers§r are useful for lots of other things too, of course. Look through the various molds to see what you can make with one.

The §aHang Glider§f is a great way to cross long distances, if you're so inclined.

If you don't want to go exploring for Cows, just buy a pair of "§6Spawn Cow§f" eggs and breed them. Seriously, spend your §dcoins§f!
Are you ready to go infinite?

With creative fluids and all the automation you hopefully set up for your first Infinity Catalyst, these ingots should be easy.

Well, not easy. But... reasonble.

Congratulations.

With this, you have effecitvely infinite amounts of all fluid resources.

Despite that, the pack will still be fairly challenging to complete from here on out.

Infinite resources and power is nice, but its not everything.

A §aGrappling Hook§f is very useful in an urban enviroment.

There are lots of ways to upgrade and improve your Grappling Hook, so play around with it.

Open your inventory and look for the Baubles button, click it to reveal the additional bauble slots and put the Hook there.

The default key is §6C§r, however since quite a lot of mods occupy this hotkey you'll need to visit the controls menu to resolve the button conflicts.

Now that you've dealt with the dragon, seek the bedrock structure floating mid-air around the edge of the main island.

Carefully throw an §6Ender Pearl§r inside one (where there's a portal-looking texture) to teleport to a distant island.

Once there, gather some §6Chorus Flowers§r. You'll have to smash the flower itself to get it: simply breaking the stem of a plant will not drop the flower.

And finally, obtain some §6Draconium Dust§r. Its ore spawns in small quantities, but should be everywhere.

To get back to the main island, throw an Ender Pearl into another bedrock portal structure.

No hoops to jump through here. Smelt §6Wood Logs§f to get §6Charcoal§f. It will serve you well as a fuel source until you locate a vein of §6Coal§f.

You might want to craft Charcoal into §6Tiny Charcoal§f pieces to save some fuel. One tiny piece is enough to smelt exactly one item. Just put charcoal into the crafting grid to make some!

A §aRubber Soft Hammer§f can be used to temporarily stop a machine from functioning. This is useful when you have two machines running and both are unable to keep going because of a lack of power... let one finish then turn the other one back on with a second hit from the hammer.

§6Dislocator Pedestals§f are a very simple way of inter-dimensional transport.

Hold a §6Dislocator§f in your hand and §6sneak-right click§f to bind it to your position. Now, place it inside a Pedestal so you can travel to the bound spot anytime you want.

Before going to the Moon, you'll need §etwo Dislocators§f and §etwo Pedestals§f.

Bind one Dislocator to a location in the Overworld, then take it with you to the Moon and put it down on a Pedestal.

Bind the other Dislocator to a location on the Moon, then use the first Pedestal to return home. Place the second Dislocator on the second Pedestal, then you can warp between the two locations at will. Neat!

§aTip: Dislocators don't lose durability on use when placed in a Pedestal!
Now that you have §einterdimensional teleportation§r, you can travel to and from the Moon without launching a rocket each way.

A good, but slightly gated way of teleporting back to your telepads.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Claim Your Chunks and Invite Teammates!
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
You might be wondering what chunkloading options there are in the pack.

Open your inventory and look at the top-left corner of the screen. Click the map-looking icon called §eClaimed Chunks§r.

§6Click a chunk§r to claim it as yours. This will prevent unwanted creeper explosions and other players from interacting with your base.

§6Shift-left click a claimed chunk§r to load it. This will ensure that the chunk is loaded at all times, even when you're not there. Alternatively, there are §achunk-loading wards§f from §bExtra Utilities§f.

§eIf you're playing on a server with custom settings, ask the server owner what methods are available§f.

To invite players to your §bFTB Utils§f party, look for a corresponding button in the same corner. Parties share claimed chunks with each other. You can configure permissions for your party's claimed chunks in the party settings menu.

Basic §aFlux Capacitors§r hold a whopping lot of energy - §a10 million RF§r - and are useful for keeping your §aRF-powered§r equipment and tools charged.

Put one into your newly crafted §3CEF§r to charge it. You can then put it in your inventory to charge your items with §aRF§r, or you can leave it in the CEF to act as a §a2.5 million EU§r battery!

Flux Capacitor is a §bBauble§r, open your inventory and look for the Baubles button, click it to reveal the additional bauble slots menu and put it into any slot you wish.

Finally you can charge up all those depleted §6Dark Boots§r and §6The Ender§r swords you've looted.

Very fluxy.

A reagent used in the majority of §6Micro Miner§r missions.

There are several ways to produce §6Quantum Flux§r. All are viable, so figure out which one works best for you.

A single-block solution to all your power needs.

This baby pushes out 2.14 GRF/t per side.

The §3Multi Smelter§r is an absolute smelting unit, and is most likely the best furnace added by a mod.

It's a 3x3x3 multiblock machine capable of §esmelting huge amounts of items per second§r. By upgrading its coils and power tier, it can become capable of smelting up to literal thousands of items per second.

Hover over different coil blocks: the higher the §elevel§r, the more items a Multi Smelter can smelt per operation: §e16 items per level§r. The most basic Multi Smelter essentially does 16 items in the same time as a furnace does one. With a set of level 4 coil blocks, that jumps to 64 items per operation.

This quest doesn't ask for coils, hatches or buses: feel free to choose whatever combination you want. You'll need §a8 coil blocks§r, §a1 input bus§r, §a1 output bus§r and at least §a1 energy hatch§r of any tier.

§aLarge Plasma Turbines§r are a powerful late game method of generating power. One Large Plasma Turbine can pull out nearly 41800 EU/t when using an §aLuV Rotor Holder§r and equipped with §a100% efficiency§r rotor.

One Mark 1 Fusion Reactor doing §bOxygen Plasma§r can saturate 16 Large Plasma Turbines, resulting in almost 670000 EU/t of power gen, but it requires quite a decent infrastructure.

Don't rely on JEI too much when looking for the best plasma, fuels are displayed in a very misleading manner. A Large Plasma Turbine consumes nearly 16 buckets of plasma to run a cycle for the duration specified in JEI, and takes some time to spin up.

Space exploration isn't mandatory in this pack, so if you don't feel like exploring space with §bAdvanced Rocketry§r, then you can centrifuge §9Hydrogen§r for §eDeuterium§r instead.

Just keep in mind that it's much less rewarding to skip this and you'll need lots of Hydrogen to compensate, although you won't need too much for the first §3Microverse Projector§r.

§3Anvils§f can be used to repair §bGregTech tools§f!

You might want to get yourself an anvil instead of breaking and crafting new tools every time. Anvils§f spawn abundantly in §bLost Cities§f buildings, so go and snatch one!

Put a damaged tool inside and put some material it's made of. For example, you'll need to put §6Wrought Iron Ingots§f to repair tools made of §6Wrought Iron§f.

GregTech adds a very versatile way of augmenting machines with §aMachine Covers§r. Covers are "upgrades" that you can put on any GregTech machine, chest, or drum to expand its functionality. To work with covers, you'll need to make yourself a §aScrewdriver§r to configure covers, and a §aCrowbar§r to remove covers without having to break the machine.

Here's a quick list of what covers there are in the game, and what they do:

- §a§lFilter§r: controls what items can enter or leave through a particular side, with 9 configurable slots and whitelist/blacklist modes. You can also put a filter into a §aConveyor§r or §aRobotic Arm§r to customize what items they will move. There's also a §9Fluid§r variant of the filter, which offers the same controls and can be placed in §aPumps§f.

- §a§lOre Dictionary Filter§r: a specialized filter that uses ore dictionary entries and supports "*" as a wildcard, e. g. "§6ingotHot*§r" will match all ingots, and "§6dustTiny*§r" will match all tiny piles.

- §a§lConveyor§r: transfers items to or from an adjacent inventory.

- §a§lRobotic Arm§r: is much like §aConveyor§r, but has two additional modes: §6Keep Exact§r, which keeps the exact amount of items in the inventory, and §6Supply Exact§r which transfers the exact amount of items per operation (useful for packaging tiny piles when used with §aOre Dictionary Filter§f!). This cover is very useful for crafting automation.

- §a§lPump§r: is much like a §aConveyor§f, but for fluids.

- §a§lShutter§r: prevents any interactions with a side.

- §a§lMachine Controller§r: enables or disables a machine and/or its covers depending on whether it is receiving a redstone signal. Useful when paired with §6ME level emitters§f to keep resources in stock.

All GregTech machines have one dedicated output side, which can be set by right-clicking a side with a §aGregTech Wrench§f. This is used for ejecting items into an adjacent inventory.

To enable auto-output, open the machine GUI and click one of the buttons in the bottom-left corner: §6orange§r is items and §9blue§r is fluids.

If you want to also be able to insert items into the output side, you'll have to right-click the output side with a §aGregTech Screwdriver§r.

These features can be used to chain machines together to make processing pipelines and facilitate crafting automation with §bApplied Energistics 2§f.

You can easily automate most §bGregTech§r machines with §aME Interfaces§r and processing §aPatterns§r early on by using the machines's auto-output feature.

Use a §aGregTech Wrench§r to relocate the output side of a machine where you want it to be, right-click it with a §aGregTech Screwdriver§r to permit input on the output face, then put an ME Interface on that side of the machine.

Right-click the machine and enable item auto-output (§6orange box§r in the bottom-left corner of the GUI).

Now, stuff the ME Interface with processing patterns. The next time you order an item, the ME Interface will push ingredients into the machine, and the machine will push outputs back into the Interface once they're ready, completing the craft. No need to use conduits or import buses!

This modpack has §aCrafting Calculators§r. It has a steep learning curve, but once you manage to learn how to use it, it's going to be your trusty companion in calculating recipe costs.

Craft yourself one and hit the book button in the top-left corner for a quick overview how it works.

Now that you have Osmium and Iridium from the §6Tier Four Micro Miner§r, you can begin automating §bExtended Crafting§r recipes. While it is possible to use §6Automation Interfaces§r for this task, you have access to something §nvastly§r better§r: §bPackagedExCrafting§r.

To begin, you'll need to craft one of each extended §3Package Crafter§r listed on the right. Put an §3Unpackager§r on top of each one, and then a §3Packager§r on top of each Unpackager. These are all AE2 devices, so you'll need to connect them to an ME Network.

Next, right-click the §3Recipe Package Encoder§r, and you should see a button saying "Processing": this button cycles through recipe types, including the various Extended Crafting tables. You'll have to choose the appropriate table for the recipe you want to encode.

§6Holders§r must be encoded in pairs: one for the Packager, and one for the Unpackager. Select the appropriate table for the recipe, look up the recipe you want to encode, and press §6[+]§r in §bJEI§r to fill it in. Put two Holders in the top-left slot and press Save to encode the recipe to both of them. Finally, put each Holder into the respective machines.

If you've done everything correctly, you should see the item appear as craftable in a Terminal.

While it might seem that the crafting process is slow, §ePackagedAuto is excellent at parallelizing§r. You can surround an Unpackager with Crafters and it will use all of them. It's also possible to add more Unpackagers with Crafters to keep up with the Packager, as long as the Holders are all the same.

required for the progression

obligatory reminder to use appropriate energy hatches

quantum compressor must face the controller

§bPackagedAuto§r is an addon for §bApplied Energistics 2§r. Its main purpose in Omnifactory is to allow you to automate extended crafting recipes.

Applied Energistics 2 stores recipes in §6Patterns§r, but they are limited to at most 9 stacks of items (a standard 3x3 crafting grid). PackagedAuto stores recipes in §6Holders§r, which don't have this limitation. Additionally, each Holder can store up to §e20 different recipes§r. Holders must be encoded in the §3Recipe Package Encoder§r.

In the vast majority of situations you'll need two identically-encoded Holders, as the following machines work together.

The §3Packager§r is a machine that compresses ingredients for a specific recipe into a set of §6Recipe Packages§r. Each package in a set can hold up to 9 stacks of ingredient items. A simple recipe might consist of one package, but a complex recipe can have up to 9 packages in its set (for 81 total item stacks).

The §3Unpackager§r is a machine that extracts ingredient items from complete sets of Recipe Packages made in a Packager, ejecting the items into an adjacent inventory. It will only extract the items if §eall packages in a set are present§r.

When both a Packager and Unpackager are connected to an ME Network and have the same recipe, the resulting item will appear as craftable in your Terminal.

Unlike §aRF power§r, which is safe to transport in any §6conduit§r, §aEU power §r§erequires caution§r. The key is to always §amatch or exceed§r the §eVoltage §rand §eAmperage§r of your power source with your §6cables§r and machines.

§o§4§cNEVER §rhook up your CEF§r to a cable that has fewer §eAmps§r than your CEF or Battery Buffer§r generates. For example, you must use §64x cable§r for a 4x CEF§r, and §616x cable§r for a filled 16-slot Battery Buffer§r. Cables with insufficient amperage rating will §cburn and be destroyed§r. Similarly, your cable must match or exceed the §eVoltage§r of your machines, or they will §cburn and be destroyed§r.

§cNEVER§r connect a machine to excessive §eVoltage§r or it will §cvaporize§r. Touching a §6wire§r with connected §aEU power§r will §cinjure or kill you§r, so for your safety, §euse §6cables§e instead§r!

§3Battery Buffers§r are §bGregTech machines§r which can be filled with §aEU Batteries§r to provide §eone amp of power per battery they contain§r. These come in 1§r, 4§r, 9§r, and 16-slot§r variations.

obligatory reminder to check energy hatches

quantum compressors must all be facing the controller

your ad here

The §3Lunar Mining Station§r is a large multiblock structure used for mining gases from the moon. It is an excellent (though not the only) source of §9Deuterium§r or §9Helium-3§r, depending on what kind of §6Rover§r you use.

Rovers only have a 10% chance to break while mining, so a stack of them will last quite a while.

Because this structure must be placed on the Moon, it is a good idea to use mechanisms like §aEnder Tanks§r or a §6Quantum Link Chamber§r for teleporting the fluids back to your base.

Make sure to keep it chunk-loaded!

§3Fluid Extractors§r are useful for melting things into liquids. For example, you can melt down ingots into molten metals, or §6Rubber Sheets§r into liquid §9Rubber§r.

When you have access to §6Steel§r, you can make molds and use §3Fluid Solidifiers§r to form various components more efficiently from fluids, like §6Gears§r.

A §3Centrifuge§r is a machine that separates things by spinning them really fast. These can be used on both items and fluids.

Notably, centrifuges can get you byproducts from the §6Impure§r and §6Purified Dusts§r that you get while processing ores. Centrifuges are generally a better alternative to tossing dusts in a Cauldron.

Now that you have a §aFlux Capacitor§r to keep things charged, you might consider making yourself a §aFluxomagnet§r.

This relatively inexpensive bauble will suck nearby items into your inventory.

Fish Oil comes from, surprisingly, fish.

Aeügh.
A much more efficient version of the Empowerer.

Useful to carry more stuff.

What more explanation are you expecting?
You'll need a Compressor for a variety of things, but probably most importantly is the ability to make plates from a single ingot.

An §3Autoclave§r is a machine that uses liquids (usually water) to polish stones, carve gems into lenses, infuse gems with special liquids, and crystallize various dusts.

You'll need an Autoclave for many recipes, but right now you want it to make §6Certus Quartz Crystals§r for §bApplied Energistics§r out of the §bGregTech§r §6Certus Quartz§r and its dust you get from mining and ore processing.

§aLumberaxes§f are tools that cut all connected blocks of the same kind (usually referred to as "§eveinmining§f") that require an axe. These are primarily intended to §echop down entire trees§f, but you can use them to veinmine other wooden blocks too.

§l§c§lKeep in mind that the veinmining feature doesn't get disabled when sneaking!§r

Please be careful to not veinmine your entire Storage Drawers network; this WILL end in tears.

Is it expensive? Yes. Is it worth it? Hell yes.

It doesn't start to shine until you get the good upgrades for it though, so maybe hold off for a while.

This terminal allows you to interact with fluid storage on your ME Network, like §aFluid Storage Disks§r.

Put fluids in or remove fluids via this terminal with any GUI-compatible container, by clicking on a fluid to fill it, or an empty space to drain into the network.

It's a micropart, so you need to place it on §6ME Cable§r (not a conduit).

§aStorage Drawer Controllers§r are the central hub of any good storage system. They can pull from any drawers they are connected to (via other drawers, or drawer trims) within a 12 block cubic radius. This leads to a potential 25x25x25 area to connect drawers, centered on the controller.

§aController Slaves§r do not extend the range, but rather act as another access point to that controller - allowing you to push/pull from any of the drawers within range of the local Drawer Controller.

Connecting an §6ME Storage Bus§f to a controller exposes all of the drawers to §bApplied Energistics§f. Particularly large networks can be laggy though, so keep your drawer networks a manageable size.

§bStorage Drawers§f provide a huge amount of storage for a single item type. Use them for things you have a lot of, such as stone, dirt and ores.

If the default appearances aren't your style, the §3Framing Table§f is useful for making custom drawers out of §6Framed Drawers§f and up to three additional items which define how the resulting drawer will look.
Great for automatically converting between Nuggets, Ingots, and Blocks of metals, or simply storing massive amounts of things.

When making circuits, you'll need either molten §9Tin§r, or molten §9Soldering Alloy§r§r§r in the §3Assembling Machine§r. Soldering Alloy is made in the §3Alloy Smelter§r with a 9:1 ratio of §6Tin Ingots§r to §6Antimony Dust§r. You then process it in a §3Fluid Extractor §rfor the usual 144mB of fluid per ingot.

The Assembling Machine will only consume half as much Soldering Alloy as it would have consumed molten Tin per craft (72mB vs 144mB), so it's very efficient to use this stuff.

Put your §3Centrifuge§r to work for the §6Antimony§r you'll need, which comes in tiny piles from processing §6Tetrahedrite Ore§r and §6Stibnite Ore§r.

Now that you have a §3Wiremill§r, you can turn one §6Copper Wire§r into four §6Fine Copper Wire§r. The recipes for §6Resistors§r, §6LV Motors§r and §6Vacuum Tubes§r all accept either type, so doing this extra processing step will make your §6Copper Ingots§r go §efour times further§r when making circuits.

You'll be making a lot more circuits from here on out, so its definitely worthwhile to save your copper!

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth And Final Tier Three Circuits
betterquesting:10.desc:8: With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §bNanocircuit§r.
A small appetizer, before the Omnium main couse.

§6Capacitors§r are devices that store electrical energy, which is useful for circuits.

Not to be confused with §bEnderIO§r's capacitors§r, which store redstone flux.

Note: this quest accepts both LV and MV Brewery.

You can turn §6Plant Balls§r and other various §6sugary crops§r into §9Biomass§r with a §3Brewery§r. Biomass is the first step towards making Plastic in the form of §9Polyethylene§r.

The Brewery is a very very slow machine, but it requires almost no power. Building higher tier Breweries, or many LV ones, is necessary to brew enough Biomass for plastics.

§9Ethanol§r is alcohol, which you can first produce from distilling §9Biomass§r.

Boiling §6Sugar Cane§r in a §3Brewery§r is a great way to get Biomass, but you can also get it from other crops and saplings if you want.

Once you have a hefty starting stock of Ethanol, consider making and distilling §9Fermented Biomass§r in a §3Distillation Tower§r for extra chemicals.

You'll need §9Chlorine§r at this point. It is an important ingredient in many chemical processes. You can get it from electrolyzing §6Salt§r, among other sources.

Using a §3Mixer§r, you can create §9Salt Water§r and electrolyze that instead of plain Salt, which §edoubles the yield per Salt§r and provides you with useful §6Sodium Hydrodixe§r (NaOH).

§bEnderIO§r and §bThermal§r alloys are a bit more expensive than the normal wires, but they come with the huge advantage of being §elossless§r. Lossy cables like §6Tin§r and §6Copper§r will bleed out energy for every block they travel, but lossless ones do not.

The lossless cables for each tier are:

LV - Conductive Iron Cables
MV - Energetic Alloy Cables
HV - Vibrant Alloy Cables
EV - End Steel Cables
IV - Lumium Cables
LuV   - Signalum Cables
ZPMV - Enderium Cables

When you first started the pack, we told you that ore doubling can wait, and that's true... But you will need to start doing some rudimentary ore processing for §ebyproducts§r.

Byproducts are additional materials that can only be obtained from processing ores in certain machines. For example, there is no "Gallium Ore". You get §6Gallium§r as a byproduct from processing other ores.

Ores have various means of processing, and eventually you'll use machine pipelines to process ores in specific ways to optimize what byproducts you gain. You can walk through JEI to figure out the path you want for each ore (always look for machine sources of small and tiny piles too).

The relevant machines are as follows:
 
- §3Macerator§r: turns ores into §6Crushed Ores§r, Crushed Ores into §6Impure Dusts§r, and §6Purified Crushed Ores§r into §6Pure Dusts§r. Higher tiers of macerators have byproduct slots and gain a chance to get a full pile of byproduct from ores and both types of crushed ores.

- §3Washer§r: cleans Crushed Ores with §9Water§r, making Purified Crushed Ores§r, and a guaranteed 3 tiny piles of byproduct. Using §9Distilled Water§r makes them go faster. This is an improved alternative to dropping dusts in a Cauldron.

- §3Chemical Bath§r: similar to a washer, but uses chemicals to purify the crushed ores. Has a chance to give a full pile of byproducts, often different than what the Washer would give.

- §3§3Centrifuge§r: separates Pure or Impure dusts into the final material, producing a guaranteed 3 tiny piles of byproduct.

- §3Electrolyzer§r: uses power to split compounds into individual elements, sometimes gaining useful byproducts in the proces.

The §3Thermal Centrifuge§r, not to be confused with the regular Centrifuge, can be used for alternative ore processing but is §edreadfully slow and power-hungry§r. No LV form exists, and its primary use is for §bNuclearCraft§r fusion fuels.

Your first forays into ore processing for byproducts will be the Electrolyzer and the Centrifuge.
